Editors:



 Bernhard Reus, Achim Jung, Klaus Keimel, Thomas Streicher:
.

The Workshop on Domains is aimed at computer scientists and mathematicians alike who share an interest in the mathematical foundations of computation. 

Domain theory has had applications to programming language semantics and logics (lambda-calculus, PCF, LCF), recursion theory (Kleene-Kreisel countable functionals), general topology (injective spaces, function spaces, locally compact spaces, Stone duality), topological algebra (compact Hausdorff semilattices) and analysis.

Further similar domain workshops in Swansea (2011) and Paris (2014).</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-3967248903.55695870b94847a</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>true</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:presentationType>workshop facilitator</gtr:presentationType><gtr:primaryAudience>Participants in your research and patient groups</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.informatics.sussex.ac.uk/events/domains9/</gtr:url><gtr:year>2008</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>The funded activity was a workshop so the findings that have been communicated stem from other projects and it is impossible to say for the workshop organiser how they have been used (this will be reported in the participant's impact reports if research was sponsored). 
